{
  "texts": [
    "In the context of authorship in science, these debates often fall to the making of the clear distinctions between the individual, as author, and technology as either a tool or sociotechnological determinant.",
    "However, by approaching the problem of academic authorship in relation to disruptive technologies using autopoiesis drawn from social systems theory, we can conceptualize author and technology as both distinct but at the same time not exclusive to one another.",
    "Both author and technology are considered as autopoietic systems whose distinctiveness are achieved through recursion of practices, actions, and meanings by the author in relation to a scientific system constituted within a medium of knowledge and the recursion of causal operations within the technology.",
    "These autopoietic systems are operationally closed but informationally open to their environments; their recursion and their stabilization of forms provide continuity but are susceptible to external irritation and new stabilizations and new continuities.",
    "This shifts the focus away from orthodox, human-centered approaches which tends to fixate on individual agency, subjectivity, and authenticity in the authorial process."
  ]
}